{{Infobox NRHP | name = Central City Opera House | nrhp_type = | image = 1982-06-22-Central City Col L 07-ps.jpg | caption = The Opera House in 1982 | location= Eureka St., [[Central City, Colorado]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|48|4|N|105|30|47|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Colorado#USA | built = 1878 | architecture = [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Renaissance Revival]]<ref name=nrhpdoc /> | added = January 18, 1973 | area = {{convert|1|acre}} | governing_body = Private | refnum = 73000474<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref> }}
The '''Central City Opera House''' is located in the [[Central City/Black Hawk Historic District]] in [[Central City, Colorado]], United States. It was constructed in 1878.<ref name="Leggett">{{cite book|last=Leggett|first=Ann|title=Insiders' Guide® to Boulder and Rocky Mountain National Park|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SI2M91foS7IC&pg=PA171|date=August 18, 2009|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7627-5624-7|page=171}}</ref> It has offered operatic and theatrical productions that drew prominent actors and performers in the late 19th-century, and in the early 20th-century it was a motion picture theatre.
The opera house was designated to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1973.<ref name=nrhpdoc>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=73000474}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Central City Opera House |publisher=[[National Park Service]]|author=Liston E. Leyendecker|date=January 13, 1973 |accessdate=June 15, 2018}} With {{NRHP url|id=73000474|photos=y|title=accompanying photos}}</ref>{{efn|There are some sources that state that the opera house was made a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1973.<ref name="Fisher2015">{{cite book|last=Fisher|first=James|title=Historical Dictionary of American Theater: Beginnings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w_6dCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA99|date=April 16, 2015|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-0-8108-7833-4|page=99}}</ref> It is the entire [[Central City/Black Hawk Historic District]] that is on the [[list of National Historic Landmarks in Colorado]].<ref name="nrhpinv">{{cite web|url={{NHLS url|id=66000246}} <!--"Central City-Black Hawk Historic District", July 1990, by Rickey L. Hendricks and Julie A. Corona --> |format=pdf|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination|date=July 1990|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>}}
==Construction and subsequent renovations== In 1877, the citizens of Central City formed the Gilpin County Opera House Association to fundraise for the state's first [[opera house]].<ref name=nrhpdoc /><ref name="Brown pp. 173–179" /> [[Denver]] architect [[Robert S. Roeschlaub]] designed the [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Renaissance Revival]] stone and brick structure,<ref name=nrhpdoc /> with a crescent-shaped balcony and arched windows.<ref name="NYT" /> [[San Francisco]] artist [[John C. Massman]] painted a mural to the ceiling with a central medallion that features the sky, surrounded by a large geometrical patter, and [[trompe-l'œil]] architectural moldings.<ref name=nrhpdoc />
It was built by Welsh and Cornish miners and town residents, who had a tradition of music,<ref name="Loomis" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Satterthwaite|first=Ann|title=Local Glories: Opera Houses on Main Street, Where Art and Community Meet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LXOhCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT207|date=February 23, 2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-939256-8|page=207}}</ref> and some of the best building professionals in the area.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} The opera house is kept cool during the summer by a creek flows that through a flume under the building.<ref name="NYT" /> Electricity was installed in 1896 and it was renovated, without structural changes in 1903.<ref name=nrhpdoc />
In 1929 a dedicated band of Denver preservationists and music lovers formed the Central City Opera House Association to perform a renovation and re-open the opera house. It was a volunteer-driven effort led by [[Ida Kruse McFarlane]], Edna Chappell and [[Anne Evans (arts patron)|Anne Evans]] that resulted in an extensive restoration of the Opera House in 1932.<ref name="Brown pp. 173–179" /> In the 1980s and 1990s, the entire structure was restored, including the foundation and replacement of the 1920-era lighting relic by a computerized lighting system. In 1999, wooden chairs were replaced with plush new theater seating.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}
==Productions and cinema== [[File:2013-7 s.jpg|thumb|left|upright=.9|Portrait of Edwin Booth by John Singer Sargent, 1890, which hung at The Players clubhouse. Now in the collection of the [[Amon Carter Museum of American Art]].]] With the 1878 grand opening, Central City was Colorado's cultural capital until another opera house, Tabor Grand Opera House, opened in 1881. The Opera House was not turning a profit and it expanded its repertoire to include theatre productions to increase its revenues. They featured prominent 19th-century actors such as [[Joseph Jefferson]], [[Edwin Booth]], [[Fanny Janauschek|Madame Januschek]] and Fannie Barlow.<ref name=nrhpdoc /> In addition, [[Buffalo Bill]] performed here as well as [[P. T. Barnum]]'s circus.<ref name="Brown pp. 173–179" /><ref name="Heim" />
Peter MacFarlane, who was a contractor for the original construction and the contractor for the 1903 renovation, became the principal owner of the Opera House by 1910, when he opened it as a motion picture theatre. The Opera House closed in 1927.<ref name=nrhpdoc />
[[File:Lillian Gish-edit1.jpg|thumb|upright=.9|[[Lillian Gish]], 1921]] The opera house was donated to the [[University of Denver]] in May 1931 by MacFarlane's heirs and restoration was organized by the newly formed Central City Opera House Association.<ref name=nrhpdoc /> The summer of 1932, actress [[Lillian Gish]] opened the newly restored opera house with ''Camille''.<ref name=nrhpdoc /><ref name="Brown pp. 173–179">{{cite book|author=Robert L. Brown|title=Central City and Gilpin County: Then and Now|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L5c3pNX80loC&pg=PA179|year=1994|publisher=Caxton Press|isbn=978-0-87004-363-5|pages=173–179}}</ref> It began a tradition of offering summer opera and theater festivals, which have become nationally recognized.<ref name=nrhpdoc />
[[File:Rossini's The Barber of Seville (Nov 14 - Dec 5, 2015) (16165089663).jpg|thumb|left|upright=.9|[[Gioachino Rossini]]'s ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'', performed by the [[Central City Opera]] November 14 - December 5, 2015)]] The [[Central City Opera]] company was also formed that year.<ref>{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Craig A.|title=A Vision of Voices: John Crosby and the Santa Fe Opera|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Iu3DBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT62|date=May 1, 2015|publisher=University of New Mexico Press|isbn=978-0-8263-5576-8|page=PT62}}</ref> It is fifth the oldest opera company in the United States.<ref name="Loomis">{{cite book|last=Loomis|first=Christine|title=Colorado Off the Beaten Path®: Discover Your Fun|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=22A0DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA18|date=August 1, 2016|publisher=Globe Pequot Press|isbn=978-1-4930-2634-0|page=18}}</ref> One of its popular performances is ''[[The Ballad of Baby Doe]]'', which tells the story of wealthy mine-owner [[Horace Tabor]] and his second wife [[Baby Doe Tabor]]. It was first performed in 1956.<ref name="NYT" /> In 2001, it was the first opera company in the United States to produce ''[[Gloriana]]'' of [[Elizabeth I]] by [[Benjamin Britten]]. [[Gioachino Rossini]]'s ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'' was performed by the [[Central City Opera]] in 2015.<ref name="Leggett pp. 172–173">{{cite book|last=Leggett|first=Ann|title=Insiders' Guide® to Boulder and Rocky Mountain National Park|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SI2M91foS7IC&pg=PA172|date=August 18, 2009|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7627-5624-7|pages=172–173}}</ref>
[[Samuel Ramey]] and [[Beverly Sills]] have performed at the opera house. It was noted by Daniel Rule, who managed the Central City Opera company, that 29 of the performers of the [[Metropolitan Opera]] in New York had performed at Central City. The Central City Opera House Association owns 30 Victorian houses in town that are used during the summer to board singers who perform at the opera house.<ref name="NYT">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/10/travel/grand-opera-in-a-colorado.html |title=Grand Opera In a Colorado |last=Arsone |first=Sarah |date=June 10, 1990 |work=The New York Times |access-date=June 16, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Up until 2000 all of the operas were performed in English. Central City Opera now performs all of its operas in their original languages.<ref name="NYT" />
The opera house continues to offer several operatic productions each summer and screenings of silent and classic films.<ref name="Leggett pp. 172–173"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Arts America: Enjoying the Best Art Museums, Theater, Classical Music, Opera, Jazz, Dance, Film, and Summer Festivals in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Nl__jDIuHIC&pg=PA354|date=March 17, 2014|publisher=Huntington Press Inc|isbn=978-1-935396-04-8|page=354}}</ref>
==Popular culture== * It was a film location for the movie ''[[The Duchess and the Dirtwater Fox]]'' starring [[Goldie Hawn]] and [[George Segal]].<ref name="Heim">{{cite book|last=Heim|first=Michael|title=Exploring Colorado Highways: Trip Trivia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3YAfcwzcfGEC&pg=PA81|year=2007|publisher=Exploring America's Highway|isbn=978-0-9777301-0-0|page=81}}</ref>
